post_text:
GVHS Art faculty are proud to present the GVHS Virtual Art Exhibition 2020! It has been challenging but we have assembled over 700 student artworks. This represents our curriculum in drawing, painting, digital media, printmaking, photography, film & animation, pottery, and sculpture. We emphasized works that demonstrate creative problem solving and perseverance: important skills that are developed throughout our art program.
Please click on the link https://bit.ly/VirtualArtShow2020 and enjoy - and share with friends and family!

text:
GVHS Art faculty are proud to present the GVHS Virtual Art Exhibition 2020! It has been challenging but we have assembled over 700 student artworks. This represents our curriculum in drawing, painting, digital media, printmaking, photography, film & animation, pottery, and sculpture. We emphasized works that demonstrate creative problem solving and perseverance: important skills that are developed throughout our art program.
Please click on the link https://bit.ly/VirtualArtShow2020 and enjoy - and share with friends and family!

post_text:
Dear School Community,

Out of an abundance of caution, we are closing Garnet Valley High School today, Friday, March 13th for a deep cleaning. There will be no school or extracurricular activities for students, and the building will be closed for the remainder of the weekend. Teachers and office staff are to work from home. We learned that one of our high school students was in proximity to an individual who tested positive for COVID 19. The high school administration is in communication with the family, and I have a report into the PA Department of Health.

Our district and the rest of Delaware County continues to be in an extremely fluid situation. Information is changing quickly, so I urge the school community to pay attention to their emails and check our website throughout the day today and for the rest of the weekend.

Thank you and make sure to take good care.

post_text:
EARLY DISMISSAL DUE TO IMPENDING WEATHER:
We dismissing students an hour early today. Also, there will be no PM Kindergarten. Secondary students will be dismissed at approximately 1:30 and elementary students at 2:10. We are currently receiving weather alerts showing snow and freezing rain at the time of our dismissals. We, consequently, wanted to give our bus drivers a head-start on getting our students home well before rush hour traffic while also avoiding the potential dangerous weather. I apologize for the late notice to parents, but the forecast really changed on us. Therefore, we wanted to avoid some of the difficult situations that we've had in the past with these types of weather patterns. Finally, there will be no after school activities this evening. As always, thank you so much for your understanding!! Bethel Springs Elementary School Concord Elementary School - GVSD Garnet Valley Elementary School Garnet ValleyMiddle School Garnet Valley High School #SchoolClosing

shared_text:
Senator Tom Killion
September 6, 2019 at 9:00 AM ·

I had a great time participating in the product launch of a limited-edition chicken and waffles recipe developed by middle school students in the Garnet Valley School District as part of Wawa's inaugural Future Food Scientist Program yesterday. The program offers students a unique, behind-the-scenes look at how fresh quality food and beverages are made at Wawa.

The chicken and waffles are available for the next week at the Wawa store located at 721 Naamans Creek Road in Chadds Ford, with a portion of the proceeds going to Philabundance to benefit those in need in Delaware County. I had a chance to sample the students’ recipe on my recent visit to Wawa’s headquarters. It’s fantastic!

shared_text:
Bethel Springs Elementary School HSA
August 12, 2019 at 5:08 PM ·

IT'S TIME FOR THE OPEN HOUSE!! (Well, it's soon :))

Parents and students are invited to come check out Bethel Springs and MEET THEIR TEACHERS on Wednesday, August 28th from 12:30-2:30pm.

Additional Open House Activities:
🍎 Spiritwear Sale: Check out this year's Spiritwear selection so your student is prepared for Spirit Days (aka Fridays :))
🍎 2019-2020 HSA Board Meet and Greet: Learn about exciting volunteer opportunities available from several members of this year's HSA Team
🍎 Pre-Ordered School Supply Kit Pickup: the kits will be located in the students' classrooms for pickup.
🍎 Extracurricular Activity Info for Students: Learn about joining a Girl Scout troop or taking a foreign language class

Looking forward to seeing you there!!

post_text:
Dear School Community,
This morning at the high school, a bag of pinnies, which are pieces of sportswear made of mesh used in physical education classes, was thrown near a stove in the sports snack bar area and inadvertently engaged it. The pinnies caught on fire and were quickly put out with an extinguisher. However, there was a great deal of smoke. The fire department was quickly called and all of the students were evacuated until the building was deemed safe by the fire marshal.

The high school team is currently using fans and exhaust systems to clear the smoke and improve the air quality prior to lunches. The students, teachers, and support staff were fantastic as they handled the situation with calm.

As always, thank you for your continued support!!

Sincerely,
Dr. Marc Bertrando, Superintendent
Garnet Valley School District

post_text:
The district continues to teach our students about Global Citizenship. One component of this learning is cultural awareness and appreciation, and I believe that this video: (https://www.facebook.com/Garnet-Valley-School-District-1686251681592675/?ref=aymt_homepage_panel), which was made to support Celebrate Our Heritage Night, provides a great rationale for why it is so important for us to prepare students for success in a rapidly changing global community through systemic educational opportunities that develop the understanding, appreciation, and competence to navigate the world around them.

Thank you to Erin Witmer-Yuska and the entire CES team for creating an accepting and appreciative environment for all students and their parents as they experience "school" for the first time.

post_text: Speaking of great young adults–this message is from the GVHS students who led Mini-Thon: Thank you so much to everyone who donated and supported Garnet Valley's 11th Mini-THON! Your generosity helped us raise $60,566.36 for the Four Diamonds Foundation! This money will be used to provide care for patients battling pediatric cancer and research into safer treatments and an ultimate cure for pediatric cancer. This year we made history by raising a total of over half a million dollars for Four Diamonds in our 11 years of holding a Mini-THON event! Garnet Valley High School and the Mini-THON Leadership Team is so grateful for your continued support, and we look forward to what next year will bring! Thank you!

shared_text:

The Making a Difference Awards celebrate those individuals who truly embrace the inclusion of learning differences in classrooms across Delaware County. This year the selection committee read almost two hundred nominations, Garnet Valley had the most nominations submitted. The Committee typically selects 2 winners per district–one an adult and the other a student. Student Winner-April Bondurant student at GVES; nominated by her mother Jennifer April

Adult Winner-Laura Murtaugh paraeducator at Bethel Springs; nominated by Becky Konkle

Dynamic Duo Award-Joe Boyle and Mickey Bommarito bus drivers; nominated by Catherine Peaper (parent)

Life Time Achievement Award-Vali Anderson nominated by multiple people; Vanessa Stroup nominated by multiple people.

Congratulations to our winners!!! We are blessed to live, learn, and/or work in Garnet Valley!!!

Thanks so much to Garnet Valley parent Dave Langan, Senior Regional Vice President for
Pacific Life- Retirement Solutions Division who awarded $1,000 to GVHS through Pacific Life Foundation’s 3Ts of Education Grants Program.

Each year, the Pacific Life Foundation makes grants to schools where there are concentrations of children and grandchildren of Pacific Life employees. Grants range from $1,000-$10,000 and are used to support Technology, Textbooks, or Teacher training. Since the program’s inception in 1998, the Pacific Life Foundation has given more than $8.3 million to hundreds of K-12 schools nationwide through the 3Ts of Education Grants Program.

Thanks again, Mr. Langan and thank you Pacific Life!!!!

It's been a crazy fire drill week–please see GVHS's email below:

Dear GVHS Community,
We apologize for another communication. Unfortunately, we had another unplanned event today with regard to the fire alarm. Shortly after 11:30 am the alarm was triggered by a heat detector near the metal forge, which was being used by our technology education department. We quickly discovered that this was a false alarm and there was no danger to the health, safety, and welfare of our students. Again, thank you to our students for their resiliency and cooperation with this situation and also to the quick work and collaboration among our teachers and staff.

GVHS Administrative Team

post_text:
This message was just sent by the high school administration.

Good Morning, GVHS Community,
This morning, shortly after 8 am, the fire alarm went off unplanned. We took approximately 30 seconds to confirm it was, indeed, a fire-related issue, and then immediately evacuated the building. We determined the alarm that went off was in the downstairs locker room area. The fire department arrived and confirmed that there was a faulty mechanical issue. Presently, our maintenance team is fixing the problem. Students were allowed to re-enter the building at 8:40 am and classes have resumed as normal. We are incredibly proud of our students as they were responsive and displayed the utmost patience and maturity as we worked to resolve the issue. Thank you to Concordville Fire Department and our maintenance staff for their quick response and collaboration.

post_text:
Congratulations to Lynn Lines Garnet Valley's winner of the DelCo Excellence in Teaching Award. Each year, this award recognizes outstanding and dedicated teachers serving students in Delaware County, Pennsylvania. As Lynn's principal Steve Piasecki says, "Lynn accomplishes excellence by remaining on the cutting edge in terms of teaching tools and strategies. Furthermore, she gets to know each student to determine not only the methods that will be most conducive to his/her learning, but what will spur a student to want to keep trying even when a task seems impossible." We agree with Mr. Piasecki and the credit union–Lynn epitomizes EXCELLENCE in teaching!!!

Franklin Mint Federal Credit Union created this award in 2007 in partnership with Delaware County Intermediate Unit. Recipients receive $500 toward classroom expenses and a commemorative keepsake. The recipient’s school also receives a $1,000 award. Congrats again Lynn!

The GV Summer Music Academy is designed for elementary and middle school band & orchestra students who wish to keep their performing skills sharp over the summer. Take your musicianship to the next level with our newly designed format which includes small and large ensemble settings, master classes, and fun musical games and activities. In addition to 8 face-to-face meeting dates, we will also include a blended (online) component each week!

Beginners (entering 4th grade) will get a great head start on their instrument just in time for the new school year. Intermediate students (entering grades 5-8) will have a great opportunity to refine their skills. Work with our talented Garnet Valley Instrumental Music Staff this summer in our fun and exciting GV Summer Music Academy! text:
The GV Summer Music Academy is designed for elementary and middle school band & orchestra students who wish to keep their performing skills sharp over the summer. Take your musicianship to the next level with our newly designed format which includes small and large ensemble settings, master classes, and fun musical games and activities. In addition to 8 face-to-face meeting dates, we will also include a blended (online) component each week!

Beginners (entering 4th grade) will get a great head start on their instrument just in time for the new school year. Intermediate students (entering grades 5-8) will have a great opportunity to refine their skills. Work with our talented Garnet Valley Instrumental Music Staff this summer in our fun and exciting GV Summer Music Academy! To learn more and/or to register, please visit: https://www.eschoolgarnetvalley.com/2019-summer-courses

Dear School Community,
With temperatures predicted to stay below freezing until 10 or 11AM, we are very concerned about ice on back roads and our building surrounds. As a result, we are closing schools and offices today. Although there is always a chance that the temperatures will rise quicker than anticipated, we cannot risk bringing in our students, faculty and staff in icy conditions. GV is typically just “west enough” to get caught in these crazy weather lines, and it appears that is what is happening today.

As always, thank you for your cooperation and support, and we will see everyone in school tomorrow. Spring cannot come soon enough!

Dr. Marc Bertrando, Superintendent
Garnet Valley School District

Dear School Community,
Due to the current forecast, we are proactively scheduling a 2 hour delay for schools and offices tomorrow–Tuesday February 12, 2019. Kindergarten will also run on a delay and use a modified schedule. We, however, will reassess conditions in the morning, and if we decide to close schools, we will make the call between 6:30 and 7:00AM.

As I’m sure you know, the weather service is calling for more precipitation, and the timing will be problematic for a normal start time. Additionally, temperatures are not expected to be above freezing until approximately 10AM, so the snow could linger and also mix with freezing rain. Although making a decision based on a forecast comes with risk, I know how difficult these days are for parents, and I want to give everyone plenty of time to prepare and organize their schedules.

Thank you for your cooperation and support,
Dr. Marc Bertrando, Superintendent

Dear School Community,
Schools and offices will run on a two-hour delayed schedule today–Monday, February 11, 2019. Kindergarten will also run on a delay and utilize a modified schedule. As we drove throughout the district, the precipitation was ending, but many of the back roads and neighborhoods were completely snow covered. Although we believe that conditions will improve quickly once the sun comes up, a two-hour delay will allow rush hour traffic to break-up some of the snow and ice, give everyone extra time to navigate their neighborhoods and driveways, and help our snow teams prepare district sidewalks and buses.

Unfortunately, it appears that we are in for more bad weather tomorrow, so I appreciate everyone’s patience and cooperation in advance. As always for our student drivers, if you are uncomfortable driving, please take the bus. Be careful this morning, and we’ll see you in a few hours!

Sincerely,
Marc Bertrando, Superintendent

Dear School Community,
Due to the timing of the squall, we are holding dismissal at the secondary level by ten minutes. All students, including student drivers, will be held in their last period classes for ten minutes in order to wait out what appears to be a very fast moving burst of wind and snow. We also informed student drivers that if they were uncomfortable driving to leave their cars in the high school parking lots and take the bus. We also decided to keep after school activities running because this system is not supposed to last beyond 2:40pm. For elementary parents, the delay will impact your children's dismissal times, so expect them to be a few minutes later.

I cannot express how grateful I am for your understanding and cooperation as we deal with this crazy weather system!

Sincerely,
Marc Bertrando, Superintendent

Schools will run on their normal schedules today. As we drove throughout the school community this morning, it was clear that road crews did an amazing job. As a result we are ready to open schools on time; however, if students are uncomfortable driving, please take the bus. There have been rumors that buses won’t pick up students who have not been at bus stops consistently–not true. post_text:
Part of our strategic plan for the district is to increase our partnerships with the community. Last year, our committee planned and held our first Community Partnership breakfast where we invited many local businesses to our school and invited them to be a part of the student learning here at Garnet Valley. Businesses communicated their interest in the following areas: Mentors, Business Directed Projects, Clinical Hosts, Advisory Council, and Guest Instructors.

Since then, we have made connections with Campbell’s Soup, Wedgewood Gardens, Wawa, Newlin Grist Mill, Brandywine Conservancy, and Comcast. See our video below to watch what happened when we worked together. We now are looking for input from our teachers so that we can offer more opportunities for our students and our community businesses!

post_text:
Over the past few years, our district has leveraged the eSchool@GarnetValley program to better personalize instruction for our students who have either needed or wanted to take some of their coursework online or in a blended format. This year, we are excited to offer several non-credit course options including SAT/ACT Prep (now open), Keystone Prep (now open), Horticulture (coming soon), Aquaculture (coming soon), and Drone Flying (coming soon).

All eSchool@GarnetValley courses are open to both Garnet Valley students and students from our neighboring school districts. To learn more or to register: https://www.eschoolgarnetvalley.com/noncreditcourses/

post_text:
Dear School Community,
All schools and offices will run on a two hour delayed schedule. Kindergarten will run on a modified schedule. I, along with the rest of our team, have been driving throughout the district since 3AM. Although roads and sidewalks are mostly wet, our temperature gauges never got above 32 degrees, which gave us concern about the “snow burst” forecasted between 5AM and 7AM. Additionally, there are huge puddles, downed branches, and slush in several areas but especially on the back roads. After yesterday, it’s senseless to risk another difficult commute for our students, drivers, and parents. Coming in two hours later will hopefully bring daylight and higher temperatures.

It’s been an unbelievable 24 hours, and I want you to know how much I appreciate your cooperation and support. These schedule changes are inconvenient for everyone, but we want to make sure that our students, faculty, and staff are safe.

Sincerely,
Marc Bertrando, Superintendent
Garnet Valley SD

post_text:
Dear Parents,
I’m really concerned that temperatures are not going not to rise quickly enough for our students to get home without incident. I, consequently, will dismiss our secondary students at 11:15 AM and our elementary students at 12:00 PM. Morning Kindergarten will dismiss at its usual time and there will be no PM or Extended Day Kindergarten.

I realize what a major inconvenience this change is for parents as well as the difficulty of having short notice; however, I’m not comfortable putting our students, faculty and staff at risk. At the high school, we have drivers whose first inclement driving experience will occur today, and additionally, I want to get everyone home prior to work traffic. Admittedly, I cannot seem to get last year's storm out of my mind when we kept students in school and some did not get home until after 6PM.

I truly appreciate your cooperation, understanding, and flexibility!

Sincerely,
Marc Bertrando, Superintendent
Garnet Valley School District

post_text:
Congrats the GV Module UN delegation who competed @ Temple University's OwlMUN V. 32 students from GV competed against over 400 students from 3 states on Sat. 14 of our delegates won awards including 2 of the coveted Best Delegate Gavels (Madelynn Lederer and Vishesh Patel).
Outstanding Delegate Awards went to: Dylan Hogan, Harry Markel, Evan Fenster, Max Foster, Ananya Gupta, and Morgan Dempsey.
Honorable Mention Delegate Awards were received by: Zora Markjoko, Evan Allen, Kushagra Gupta, Alex Corcoran, Atreya Ghosh, and Vikas Rana

Also, for the first time in our club's history, we brought home the big one...Best Delegation of the conference! This is the top honor in the Model UN World. #getthatgavel
